===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|單|戈|c1=p|c2=s|t2=halberd|ls=psc}} – battling with a halberd.

===Etymology===
{{zh-ref|Benedict (1972)}} thinks it a cognate to {{ncog|bo|རལ་གྲི||sword}}, {{ncog|lus|râl||enemy}}, both from {{ncog|tbq-pro|*g-raːl ~ *g-ran ~ *ray||enemy, quarrel, strife, fight, war, sword}}, yet {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} thinks it unlikely that Old Chinese *''t-'' corresponds to Tibeto-Burman *''r-''.

Instead he proposes that "war, battle" is semantically extended from "tremble, fear" and so {{och-l|戰}} is cognate with {{och-l|憚}} (ibid.); STEDT in turn derives them both from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*dar ~ d(u/i)r||tremble, shiver}}.

